WEBVTT

00:02.252 --> 00:03.503
- Previously on Haven...

00:03.629 --> 00:05.085
FBI! Who are you?
- Haven PD! Who are you?

00:05.214 --> 00:06.329
- FBI. Are you deaf?

00:06.465 --> 00:07.671
[door slams]

00:07.799 --> 00:09.630
Oh! I'm sorry.
Are you all right?

00:09.760 --> 00:11.751
- It's all right.
I didn't feel it.

00:13.263 --> 00:14.844
- So you seriously
can't feel pain?

00:14.973 --> 00:16.133
- No.

00:16.266 --> 00:17.381
- You must be Duke.

00:17.518 --> 00:18.633
- I don't talk to cops,

00:18.769 --> 00:20.134
even cops that I like.

00:20.270 --> 00:22.477
- I know that picture.
- You do?

00:22.606 --> 00:24.221
- Colorado Kid murder.

00:24.358 --> 00:26.770
She looks like you.
- Yeah, I know.

00:26.902 --> 00:29.268
This isn't the first weird thing
I've seen in Haven, Nathan,

00:29.404 --> 00:31.360
and I've only
been here a week.

00:33.909 --> 00:35.615
So just--can you tell me
what's going on?

00:35.744 --> 00:38.281
- Every town's got
a few skeletons in the closet.

00:38.413 --> 00:41.246
- Well, this is
a big freakin' closet.

00:41.375 --> 00:43.366
Your father
just offered me a job.

00:43.502 --> 00:44.662
- What'd you say?

00:44.795 --> 00:48.083
- I said
that I would think it over.

00:48.215 --> 00:49.955
- Might be a good idea.

00:50.092 --> 00:52.583
- The troubles, you're afraid
they're coming back?

00:52.719 --> 00:53.834
- No.

00:53.971 --> 00:55.507
They are back.

00:55.639 --> 00:58.051
And I'm afraid
they won't go away this time.

01:10.112 --> 01:12.603
[classical music playing]

01:12.739 --> 01:16.152
- Hey, babe, um,
I just fixed that hatch.

01:16.285 --> 01:17.525
The Caprice is almost ready

01:17.661 --> 01:19.071
to get back out
on that high seas.

01:19.204 --> 01:21.616
Maybe one day,
you and me can--

01:21.748 --> 01:23.033
can motor out
to Seal Island, huh?

01:23.166 --> 01:24.747
- [banging on piano]

01:24.876 --> 01:26.787
- It's okay. It's okay.
- How you doing, Ray?

01:26.920 --> 01:29.161
- Tired.

01:29.298 --> 01:31.254
I'm good. I'm fine.
Thanks.

01:31.383 --> 01:32.589
- You hang in there,
all right?

01:32.718 --> 01:34.208
- Okay, Lilly,
I'm gonna go home,

01:34.344 --> 01:36.130
but I'll see you
next week.

01:36.263 --> 01:38.595
- Ready?
And one, two...

01:38.724 --> 01:40.555
- HoW's William this morning?
- Three.

01:40.684 --> 01:43.767
Oh, he's a regular LeBron James
today, aren't you, William?

01:43.895 --> 01:45.305
- The doc's gonna administer.

01:45.439 --> 01:47.680
Help me with the lunches?
- Yeah, okay.

01:53.780 --> 01:56.442
-Mmm!
Chicken salad today.

01:56.575 --> 01:58.440
- Yeah, they eat well.

01:58.577 --> 02:00.192
Better than me.
- Yeah, they have to.

02:00.329 --> 02:02.115
Need a full stomach
to tolerate that medicine.

02:02.247 --> 02:03.908
[glass shatters]
- Damn it!

02:12.716 --> 02:14.877
- That's not good.

02:15.010 --> 02:16.170
Let me help you with that.

02:16.303 --> 02:17.543
- No!

02:17.679 --> 02:19.340
You're contaminating
everything!

02:24.686 --> 02:26.347
- Oh, my God!

02:28.315 --> 02:30.101
- Nice work on the cat lady call
this morning.

02:30.233 --> 02:31.359
- Who knew I had such talent

02:31.485 --> 02:32.850
with drunken women
in housecoats?

02:32.986 --> 02:34.101
- Not me.

02:34.237 --> 02:35.363
- Oh, and I did
a pretty good job

02:35.489 --> 02:36.854
with that angry fisherman dude.

02:36.990 --> 02:38.150
- Once you got his pants on.

02:38.283 --> 02:40.194
- [laughs]
Yeah, that helped.

02:40.327 --> 02:42.363
- Life of a local cop.

02:42.496 --> 02:44.657
- Hey, remember,
I'm on loan.

02:44.790 --> 02:47.281
- You'll stay.
- Oh, you think so?

02:47.417 --> 02:49.373
- Best way to find out
if your mother came through here

02:49.503 --> 02:51.118
is to be a local cop,

02:51.254 --> 02:53.245
unless you're ready to give
that investigation up.

02:53.382 --> 02:55.213
- You know I'm not.

02:55.342 --> 02:57.674
I just thought
that when l was in Haven,

02:57.803 --> 02:59.043
the cases would be more...

02:59.179 --> 03:01.386
- Troubling.

03:01.515 --> 03:03.506
I get it.

03:03.642 --> 03:05.928
Well, we'll see
more of that soon.

03:07.479 --> 03:09.015
But, you know,
don't underestimate

03:09.147 --> 03:10.478
your skills
with the small stuff.

03:10.607 --> 03:11.972
- Skills?

03:12.109 --> 03:13.565
- A local cop probably
wouldn't have put

03:13.694 --> 03:14.900
all the cats in the same box.

03:15.028 --> 03:16.768
- I only had one box.

03:16.905 --> 03:18.111
And anyways, they all fit.

03:18.240 --> 03:21.323
- Next time,
maybe just look around.

03:21.451 --> 03:22.736
- Why, did I miss something?

03:22.869 --> 03:24.325
- Mrs. Nelson's
fourth grade class

03:24.454 --> 03:25.785
watching you
from the school.

03:25.914 --> 03:28.826
- Oh, God, do you think
I scarred them?

03:28.959 --> 03:32.247
- I think they laughed
their fourth grade asses off.

03:32.379 --> 03:34.745
- Nathan,
are you there, hon?

03:37.050 --> 03:38.460
- Go ahead, Laverne.

03:38.593 --> 03:41.380
- Got a call about a disturbance
at the Freddy.

03:41.513 --> 03:42.628
- We're on our way.

03:42.764 --> 03:44.300
- What's a Freddy?

03:44.433 --> 03:46.389
You're kidding me.

03:46.518 --> 03:48.554
Haven has
a mental hospital?

03:48.687 --> 03:52.054
That's a grain of sand
at the beach.

03:52.190 --> 03:54.101
Who's Murray Q. Frederikson?

03:54.234 --> 03:55.895
- A respected local car dealer,

03:56.027 --> 03:59.110
till one day, he announced
he could breathe like a fish

03:59.239 --> 04:00.979
and disappeared
under the sea.

04:01.116 --> 04:02.947
- Let me guess.
Was that during the troubles?

04:03.076 --> 04:05.237
- Nope.
He was just crazy.

04:05.370 --> 04:07.201
His wife founded the Freddy
with his estate.

04:07.330 --> 04:08.490
- Thank God you're here!
- Whoa!

04:08.623 --> 04:09.954
[woman screams]

04:10.083 --> 04:12.244
- What's going on?
- I have no idea.

04:12.377 --> 04:14.288
l was in the kitchen.
I heard screaming.

04:14.421 --> 04:15.706
I went into the common room.

04:15.839 --> 04:17.579
Dr. Lucassi's medicine
was all over.

04:17.716 --> 04:19.297
Morgan's in there
trying to calm everyb--

04:19.426 --> 04:21.291
[glass shatters]
- Whoa!

04:21.428 --> 04:22.634
[woman screams]

04:22.763 --> 04:24.469
- Oh!

04:24.598 --> 04:27.465
- Laverne, we need backup
and a medic at the Freddy now.

04:27.601 --> 04:28.966
- What's going on, hon?

04:29.102 --> 04:31.309
- The patients
have taken over the asylum.

04:31.438 --> 04:32.803
- Morgan?
- Where are the doctors?

04:32.939 --> 04:34.600
Who's in charge?
- Him.

04:36.985 --> 04:39.101
That's Dr. Lucassi.

04:47.954 --> 04:50.821
[dramatic music]

04:50.957 --> 04:58.955
J‘J‘

05:38.380 --> 05:40.086
- Okay, come on,
just keep coming this way.

05:40.215 --> 05:43.582
- He's no bored housewife.

05:43.718 --> 05:45.629
We can't shoot the doctor.

05:45.762 --> 05:47.548
- No.

05:47.681 --> 05:49.637
- And we can't go
in that room.

05:49.766 --> 05:50.881
- [groans]

05:51.017 --> 05:53.554
-So...

05:53.687 --> 05:56.019
why are we
sneaking up on him?

05:56.147 --> 05:58.229
- Because Haven
doesn't have a SWAT team.

05:58.358 --> 06:01.191
It has a dispatch lady
that calls you hon.

06:01.319 --> 06:03.275
So we're following
FBI protocol.

06:03.405 --> 06:05.521
- [yelling]
- What's that?

06:05.657 --> 06:08.490
- Engage the suspect verbally,
attenuate, and mitigate.

06:08.618 --> 06:10.950
- Talk to him?

06:11.079 --> 06:12.364
- Yeah.

06:12.497 --> 06:13.953
- Hmm, great.

06:14.082 --> 06:15.913
- Dr. Lucassi,
this is FBI Agent--

06:16.042 --> 06:17.248
[loud crash]

06:17.377 --> 06:19.789
- Go away!
I have work to do!

06:21.548 --> 06:23.630
- Plan B.
- So much work to do!

06:23.758 --> 06:24.918
- You think we could, uh--

06:25.051 --> 06:26.882
think we could Taser him?

06:27.012 --> 06:29.219
- Don't think a Taser
will reach.

06:29.347 --> 06:31.338
- [yelling]

06:32.767 --> 06:34.632
- And given that,

06:34.769 --> 06:36.851
I'm winging it.

06:38.273 --> 06:39.513
Okay.

06:41.860 --> 06:43.100
- Ether?

06:44.779 --> 06:46.064
[glass shatters]

06:48.867 --> 06:49.982
- [coughing]

06:50.118 --> 06:51.949
- Impressive.

06:52.078 --> 06:54.160
- [coughing]

06:54.289 --> 06:55.529
[glass shatters]

06:55.665 --> 06:57.951
[coughing]

07:00.670 --> 07:02.285
- Got the doctor contained
in the Freddy

07:02.422 --> 07:03.923
pending medical's arrival.

07:04.049 --> 07:05.664
We need A.J.
to come take a sample

07:05.800 --> 07:07.791
and see if Millikin
can salvage anything

07:07.928 --> 07:11.295
off the security cameras
before they were trashed.

07:11.431 --> 07:12.967
- All right,
she did a patient head count.

07:13.099 --> 07:14.635
- We lose any?
- Three.

07:14.768 --> 07:16.304
And we need
to get to them immediately.

07:16.436 --> 07:18.176
- Dr. Lucassi's
a good man.

07:18.313 --> 07:20.804
He's a little intense,
but he wouldn't hurt a fly.

07:20.941 --> 07:23.023
- The three that escaped,
they were in the room with him

07:23.151 --> 07:24.482
when the jungle juice
spilled.

07:24.611 --> 07:26.476
- If it did to them
what it did to him...

07:26.613 --> 07:29.320
- Yeah, but do you really think
that a drug spill could do this?

07:29.449 --> 07:31.155
- Well, seen worse.

07:32.744 --> 07:34.575
I went to college.

07:39.167 --> 07:41.123
Okay, what are you thinking?

07:41.252 --> 07:42.788
- That guy looked different.

07:42.921 --> 07:44.036
- Different how?

07:44.172 --> 07:45.378
- Different like a...

07:45.507 --> 07:47.338
like a special blend
of Haven crazy.

07:47.467 --> 07:49.128
- Mm-hmm.

07:49.260 --> 07:51.000
You like it.
- Like what?

07:51.137 --> 07:52.468
- The weirdness.

07:52.597 --> 07:54.258
You hope it's something weird.

07:54.391 --> 07:56.006
That's why you're still here.

07:56.142 --> 07:58.303
- No, I'm still here
because a woman who was here

07:58.436 --> 08:00.643
could have been my mom,
and I'd like to find out.

08:00.772 --> 08:02.137
- Uh-huh. Right.

08:02.273 --> 08:04.013
And you run around
in the Mystery Machine...

08:04.150 --> 08:05.560
- Wait, Nathan.
- Are you there, hon?

08:05.694 --> 08:07.275
Prowlers reported
to be pilfering items

08:07.404 --> 08:09.861
off the laundry line,
including two pairs of shorts,

08:09.990 --> 08:11.696
four socks,
and two gray sweatshirts...

08:11.825 --> 08:13.565
- What might
escaped mental patients need?

08:13.702 --> 08:16.444
- A T-shirt and, oh,
one floppy hat.

08:16.579 --> 08:18.319
- Oh.

08:19.499 --> 08:20.614
- Thank God!

08:20.750 --> 08:21.865
They're still here!

08:22.002 --> 08:24.789
They have my son
in the back!

08:24.921 --> 08:28.505
[laughter]

08:32.679 --> 08:34.260
- Oh, hello, there!

08:34.389 --> 08:36.755
William's always been
a bit of a child at heart.

08:36.891 --> 08:39.223
I could do that, too,
if I was young and fit

08:39.352 --> 08:41.388
and him.

08:41.521 --> 08:45.514
[laughing]

08:55.035 --> 08:57.947
- Vegetables, fruit...

08:58.079 --> 08:59.194
- Lilly.

08:59.330 --> 09:01.241
- Ah!
Eggs”.

09:01.374 --> 09:03.365
- What the hell?

09:03.501 --> 09:05.207
Those twits.
How did you get out?

09:05.336 --> 09:08.954
- Hey, Ray.
What's with this fridge?

09:10.800 --> 09:13.963
12 beer, two ketchups,
and zero veggies?

09:14.095 --> 09:16.427
That's not gonna help
with your cholesterol, love.

09:19.559 --> 09:23.097
Ray?
You okay?

09:23.229 --> 09:24.344
- Yeah, yeah.

09:24.481 --> 09:27.973
Um...are you?

09:28.109 --> 09:29.315
- Yeah, I think so.

09:29.444 --> 09:30.650
It's weird.

09:30.779 --> 09:32.440
I was just walking
down Harkness.

09:32.572 --> 09:34.483
Was I in the hospital?

09:36.576 --> 09:39.818
- You...were.

09:39.954 --> 09:41.865
How are you feeling now?

09:41.998 --> 09:44.114
- A bit spacey but fine.

09:44.250 --> 09:45.456
Hungry.

09:45.585 --> 09:48.247
- Okay.
I'll make us some...

09:49.923 --> 09:52.630
[sighs]

09:52.759 --> 09:56.092
Nothing.
Got nothing.

09:56.221 --> 09:57.961
- That's okay.

09:58.098 --> 10:00.464
Maybe start
with a hello kiss.

10:10.568 --> 10:11.819
Hello.

10:13.446 --> 10:14.686
- Hi.

10:29.295 --> 10:31.877
[men speaking indistinctly]

10:32.006 --> 10:33.507
- So you're a florist.

10:33.633 --> 10:35.339
- Uh-huh.

10:35.468 --> 10:38.460
And this part of the northeast
is great for flowering vines.

10:38.596 --> 10:42.805
This beautiful flower
is a Wisteria sinensis.

10:42.934 --> 10:44.174
Spectacular plant.

10:44.310 --> 10:45.846
- Cool.

10:50.817 --> 10:52.273
What?

10:52.402 --> 10:53.517
- I remember...

10:53.653 --> 10:56.611
Gerbera daisies,

10:56.739 --> 11:00.106
snapdragons,

11:00.243 --> 11:02.700
orchids.

11:02.829 --> 11:04.865
- Okay.
Nathan?

11:04.998 --> 11:06.989
Nathan,
can I have some help here?

11:08.585 --> 11:09.700
- Whoa.

11:09.836 --> 11:11.451
Busy.

11:11.588 --> 11:13.374
Wait. Stop.

11:13.506 --> 11:14.962
- Oh.

11:15.091 --> 11:17.207
- Hey, what do you think
happened to these guys?

11:17.343 --> 11:20.301
- The excess saliva's
completely normal.

11:20.430 --> 11:21.840
It's a side effect
of his meds.

11:24.559 --> 11:26.515
Although he might be dehydrated.

11:27.770 --> 11:29.306
- Uh...are you okay?

11:29.439 --> 11:31.600
Because you weren't
a few minutes ago.

11:31.733 --> 11:33.564
- I feel fine.

11:33.693 --> 11:36.059
Though I shudder to think
what behavior got me here.

11:36.196 --> 11:39.188
William needs my help.
Can you unstrap me?

11:39.324 --> 11:41.030
-Uh...

11:43.953 --> 11:46.444
All right, go ahead.
Just”

11:46.581 --> 11:47.821
Yeah.

11:49.876 --> 11:51.412
Thank you.

11:53.713 --> 11:55.169
- Why are these men here?

11:55.298 --> 11:56.879
- Well, we're just
bringing them back.

11:57.008 --> 11:58.714
You know, they had
a trampoline playdate.

11:58.843 --> 12:01.255
- These two men
are stage three catatonics.

12:01.387 --> 12:05.255
Mr. Sperry hasn't spoken
or moved in 16 years.

12:05.391 --> 12:07.598
- Well, he was fine
up until a moment ago.

12:07.727 --> 12:08.842
You, not so much.

12:08.978 --> 12:10.934
- Doctor,
there was a spill.

12:11.064 --> 12:13.100
- Maybe it made them better

12:13.233 --> 12:14.814
and you...worse.

12:14.943 --> 12:17.184
- And oddly stronger.
- What was I doing?

12:17.320 --> 12:18.605
- You were ranting
about your work.

12:18.738 --> 12:20.103
- And contamination.

12:20.240 --> 12:22.777
- I am somewhat obsessive
about cleanliness.

12:22.909 --> 12:24.365
Perhaps whatever happened

12:24.494 --> 12:26.951
amplified my predilections
and removed inhibitions.

12:27.080 --> 12:29.992
Although I can't imagine
my drugs doing that.

12:30.124 --> 12:32.706
- At least everyone's
back the way they were.

12:32.835 --> 12:36.578
- Um, Lilly
is still out there.

12:36.714 --> 12:38.625
- Is she a catatonic?
- No.

12:38.758 --> 12:40.965
But she can be violent,

12:41.094 --> 12:42.755
extremely so.

12:49.978 --> 12:51.343
Lilly was a musician.

12:51.479 --> 12:54.937
And now she has
a grand mal obsessive disorder--

12:55.066 --> 12:57.603
akin to a PTSD,
only worse.

12:57.735 --> 12:59.441
- Is that
why she was committed?

12:59.570 --> 13:01.856
- When she feels
the music is...

13:01.990 --> 13:04.026
escaping her,

13:04.158 --> 13:07.821
she gets extremely frustrated
and destructive.

13:09.455 --> 13:10.706
- Ray McBreen?

13:10.832 --> 13:12.163
- Ah, Dr. Lucassi.

13:12.292 --> 13:14.032
l was wondering
when you were gonna show.

13:14.168 --> 13:17.456
Whatever you did for Lilly,
thank you.

13:17.588 --> 13:18.964
- She's okay?

13:19.090 --> 13:22.628
- She's great.
Come on in.

13:23.970 --> 13:26.302
LHILove?

13:28.558 --> 13:29.968
Damn it.

13:31.394 --> 13:32.804
- She must have
changed back.

13:32.937 --> 13:34.052
- How?
She was fine!

13:34.188 --> 13:35.769
- I don't know...yet.

13:35.898 --> 13:37.513
- Any idea
where she could have gone?

13:38.818 --> 13:41.480
- If she's back
the way she was--

13:41.612 --> 13:43.227
anyplace with a piano.

13:43.364 --> 13:44.524
- Why?

13:44.657 --> 13:46.318
- She wants to compose music.

13:46.451 --> 13:48.487
- Okay, let's find her.

13:48.619 --> 13:51.702
- Wait, Nathan.

13:53.583 --> 13:54.698
make sure it's causing it.

13:54.834 --> 13:56.870
- And if it isn't,
then what?

13:57.003 --> 13:59.210
- It's a simple test.

13:59.339 --> 14:01.751
- Okay, you two do that.

14:01.883 --> 14:03.373
- Yeah.

14:04.635 --> 14:06.500
- We'll find her.

14:11.059 --> 14:12.390
Why pianos?

14:12.518 --> 14:14.554
- She liked to compose on them.

14:14.687 --> 14:16.143
Said they felt right.

14:16.272 --> 14:18.479
- Ray?
- I don't want to talk about it.

14:22.028 --> 14:24.189
- Ray, talk to me.

14:24.322 --> 14:27.405
- Lilly--
Lilly loves writing music.

14:27.533 --> 14:32.323
One day, a music exec
heard one of her songs.

14:32.455 --> 14:36.494
Said if she could write another,
we had a big contract.

14:36.626 --> 14:40.164
She wanted it--
she wanted it perfect.

14:40.296 --> 14:41.957
I did too.

14:42.090 --> 14:46.254
I talked her into driving up
to her favorite composing place.

14:46.386 --> 14:48.923
We were so excited,
I got distracted

14:49.055 --> 14:53.219
and drove off the road
into the Penobscot River.

14:55.186 --> 14:57.848
I barely made it out alive.

14:57.980 --> 15:03.065
Took me another eight minutes
to get her out.

15:03.194 --> 15:05.025
Well, they said that
if the water wasn't so cold,

15:05.154 --> 15:07.065
she would have been
brain-dead.

15:09.826 --> 15:11.612
Instead she's...

15:11.744 --> 15:13.575
- Like she is.

15:17.166 --> 15:19.202
- Because of me.

15:22.088 --> 15:24.044
- Officer,

15:24.173 --> 15:26.255
have you ever had
a family member

15:26.384 --> 15:29.672
fade away
because of Alzheimer's?

15:29.804 --> 15:31.669
l have.

15:31.806 --> 15:34.718
Cruel doesn't begin
to describe it.

15:34.851 --> 15:36.637
I'd like to stop that.

15:36.769 --> 15:39.806
Identical volume
and concentration.

15:39.939 --> 15:42.806
Pray we get a measurable delta
in wattage.

15:42.942 --> 15:44.807
- Measurable delta
in wattage?

15:44.944 --> 15:48.152
- Flesh and electricity,
that's what we are.

15:48.281 --> 15:50.567
Of course, I'm sure there are
some unmeasurable energies,

15:50.700 --> 15:53.157
like our soul.

15:53.286 --> 15:55.151
- Oh, you believe in that?

15:55.288 --> 15:57.529
- A few centuries ago,
the world's best scientists

15:57.665 --> 16:00.782
were convinced
that the Earth was flat.

16:00.918 --> 16:02.704
Everything they saw about it
was flat.

16:02.837 --> 16:03.997
But was it?

16:04.130 --> 16:05.540
No.

16:05.673 --> 16:06.788
They were just afraid

16:06.924 --> 16:10.212
to open their eyes
and sail.

16:10.344 --> 16:11.754
Could you get me
those safety goggles

16:11.888 --> 16:13.128
out there, please?

16:19.020 --> 16:22.103
- Wait!
What are you doing?

16:22.231 --> 16:24.062
- Scientific method.
- Get out of there!

16:24.192 --> 16:28.401
- Calculated risk is critical
to great discoveries.

16:28.529 --> 16:30.986
[glass shatters]

16:31.115 --> 16:33.527
- Doctor, you need
to get out of there!

16:33.659 --> 16:36.651
[instrument beeping]

16:43.085 --> 16:45.701
- Why isn't this working?
What's different?

16:52.470 --> 16:55.052
- J‘ Farewell and adieu
to you J‘

16:55.181 --> 16:56.637
- Where'd you get that?

16:56.766 --> 16:58.927
- Came with the Happy Meal.
- Yeah, right.

16:59.060 --> 17:00.721
- All right, you caught me.

17:00.853 --> 17:03.845
Ah, Nate, the Scupper
was giving it away.

17:03.981 --> 17:06.188
I was gonna use it
to decorate the boat.

17:06.317 --> 17:08.774
Now, do I need a permit
for that, Officer,

17:08.903 --> 17:11.235
or is it gonna be okay?

17:19.914 --> 17:21.279
You know
what's amazing, Nate?

17:21.415 --> 17:24.248
Is that you get a badge,
you get to harass me.

17:24.377 --> 17:27.369
- Because you're
a lowlife criminal.

17:32.009 --> 17:33.670
- I'm gonna check inside.

17:37.348 --> 17:38.588
- New partner?

17:40.560 --> 17:41.675
I don't know.

17:41.811 --> 17:43.176
I kind of liked
the old one better.

17:43.312 --> 17:45.598
Let me ask you something.
Does she...

17:45.731 --> 17:51.271
I mean, does she know
you're not a...

17:51.404 --> 17:52.644
a real boy?

17:54.907 --> 17:57.114
I mean, does she know
about the things you've done?

17:59.954 --> 18:01.740
- Hey.
She's here.

18:06.919 --> 18:08.910
- Have a nice day, Nate.

18:22.476 --> 18:24.967
- This is what we got
off the security camera.

18:25.104 --> 18:28.016
- Okay, this should be
the spill.

18:29.066 --> 18:30.727
- Hmm.

18:30.860 --> 18:34.773
- It's like ljust dropped it,
like I felt something.

18:34.905 --> 18:37.897
- Okay, let's rewind it
to right before the spill.

18:38.951 --> 18:40.987
There.

18:41.120 --> 18:43.987
Wait.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.205
Is that William?

18:46.334 --> 18:49.542
He's--he's already
holding the ball.

18:54.884 --> 18:57.421
Nathan, whatever caused it
happened before the spill.

18:57.553 --> 18:58.918
It was something
invisible.

18:59.055 --> 19:00.420
- Okay.
Listen--

19:00.556 --> 19:01.887
- I don't know
if it was a gas or a virus

19:02.016 --> 19:03.677
or if it was something weird,

19:03.809 --> 19:05.845
but when we checked the tape,
we figured that it was--

19:05.978 --> 19:08.845
- Audrey,
we found Lilly.

19:08.981 --> 19:11.017
[soft piano notes]

19:11.150 --> 19:12.765
- How is she?

19:12.902 --> 19:15.564
- She's trying
to play the piano.

19:15.696 --> 19:17.937
Can't get it out of neutral,
though.

19:18.074 --> 19:19.860
- Let's get you back
to the Freddy, baby.

19:19.992 --> 19:27.990
